Sometimes, I feel ashamed to be a European.
Last year, over a million people in need of our help arrived in Europe, and our response was frankly pathetic.
There are so many contradictions.
We mourn the tragic death of Alan Kurdi, a two-year-old child, and yet, since then, over 200 children have drowned in the Mediterranean.
International treaties recognize that refugees are a collective responsibility, and yet we accept that small Lebanon is hosting more Syrians than all of Europe combined.
We lament the existence of smugglers, yet we make it the only viable route to seek asylum in Europe.
We are lacking labor, yet we prevent people who match our economic and demographic needs from coming to Europe.
We proclaim our liberal values in opposition to fundamentalist Islam, yet -- we have repressive policies that detain minor asylum seekers, separate children from their families, and confiscate the belongings of refugees.
What are we doing?
How did we end up here, adopting such an inhumane response to a humanitarian crisis?
I do not believe that this is due to a lack of interest, at least I do not want to believe it.
I believe it is because our politicians lack vision, that they do not know how to adapt the international asylum rules, created more than 50 years ago, to globalization.
I want to take a step back and ask two fundamental questions, the two questions that we all must ask.
First, why is the current system not working?
Secondly, how can we remedy this?
The current regime for refugees was established in response to the consequences of the Second World War by these people.
Its primary aim is to ensure that when a state fails, or worse, turns against its people, individuals have a place to go, to live in safety and with dignity until they can return.
It was created specifically for situations such as the current situation in Syria.
Through an international convention signed by 147 governments, the 1951 Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees, and an international organization, the UNHCR, states have committed to mutually admitting individuals fleeing conflict and persecution onto their territory.
But today, this system is failing.
In theory, refugees have the right to apply for asylum.
In practice, our immigration policies block the path to safety.
In theory, refugees have the right to integration or to return to their country of origin.
But in practice, they remain stuck in eternal limbo.
In theory, refugees are a global common responsibility.
In practice, geography means that countries close to the conflict host the overwhelming majority of refugees.
The system is not broken because the rules are bad.
but because we do not apply them adequately to a changing world, and that is what we must reconsider.
