How does the current regime for refugees work?
But not from an institutional perspective, rather from the point of view of a refugee.
Imagine a Syrian woman. Let's call her Amira.
For me, Amira represents
many people I have met in the region.
Amira, like 25% of refugees worldwide, is a woman with children, and she cannot return home because she comes from that city you see: Homs. A city that was beautiful and historic and is now in ruins.
Amira cannot go back there.
But Amira has no hope of settling in a third country, because there is a lottery available to only less than 1% of refugees.
Amira and her family are facing an impossible choice.
They have three options.
The first option is for Amira to take her family to a camp.
In the camp, she could receive help, but there is little future for Amira and her family.
The camps are in austere and arid places, often in the desert.
In the Zaatari camp in Jordan, at night, you can hear the bombings from the other side of the border.
Economic activity is restricted.
Education is often of poor quality.
Around 80% of refugees in camps worldwide must remain there for at least 5 years.
It is a miserable life, and that is probably why, in reality, only 9% of Syrians choose this option.
An alternative for Amira is to head towards the urban area of a neighboring country, such as Amman or Beirut.
It is an option chosen by approximately 75% of Syrian refugees.
But it also involves difficulties.
Refugees in such urban areas often do not have the right to work.
They often do not have access to assistance.
And so when Amira and her family have spent all their savings, they will have nothing left and will be in urban poverty.
There is a third option that an increasing number of Syrians are choosing.
Amira can seek hope for her family by risking their lives on a dangerous and perilous journey to another country, and this is what we are witnessing today in Europe.
We are therefore offering refugees an almost impossible choice between three options: encampment, urban poverty, or a dangerous journey.
For refugees, this choice is the refugee regime of today.
But I believe it is a false choice.
We can reconsider this choice.
The reason we limit these options is because we think they are the only possible options for refugees, but that is not the case.
Policymakers see this as a zero-sum problem; if we benefit the refugees, citizens pay the price.
We tend to think of refugees as an inevitable cost or a burden on society.
