What I mean is that there are ways to increase opportunities that benefit everyone: the host countries and communities, our societies, and the refugees.
And I want to suggest four ways to transform our view of refugees.
These four perspectives have one thing in common: they incorporate the opportunities of globalization, mobility, and markets, and modernize our way of thinking about the refugee issue.
The first idea is that of favorable environments. It begins with the fundamental recognition that refugees are human beings like everyone else, but with extraordinary circumstances.
With my colleagues from Oxford, we embarked on a research project in Uganda, observing the economic life of refugees.
We chose Uganda not because it is representative of all host countries.
It is exceptional.
Unlike most host countries, Uganda has provided economic opportunities for refugees.
It grants them the right to work and the freedom of movement.
And the results are extraordinary, for the refugees and for the host community.
In the capital, Kampala, we discovered that 21% of refugees own a business employing people, and 40% of these employees are natives of the host country.
In other words, refugees create jobs for the citizens of the host country.
Even in the camps, we discovered extraordinary examples of dynamic and thriving businesses.
For example, in a village named Nakivale, we have the example of Congolese refugees running digital music sharing businesses.
We found a Rwandan who runs a business to allow young people to play video games on recycled consoles and televisions.
Despite the challenges of extreme constraints, refugees are innovating, and the man you see is a Congolese named Demou-Kay.
Demou-Kay arrived at the camp with very few belongings, but he wanted to become a filmmaker.
So, with friends and colleagues, he launched a community radio station, rented a camera, and makes films.
He has made two documentaries with and for our team, and he is in the process of creating a successful business with almost nothing.
These are the kinds of examples that should guide our response to refugees.
Rather than seeing refugees as inevitably dependent on humanitarian aid, we must provide them with the opportunity for human development.
Yes, clothing, blankets, shelter, and food are very important in the emergency phase, but we must go further.
We must provide the opportunity for connectivity, electricity, education, the right to work, and access to banks.
Everything we take for granted, which integrates us into the global economy, can and should be offered to refugees.
The second idea I want to discuss is economic zones.
Unfortunately, not all host countries in the world have the approach that Uganda does.
Most host countries do not open their economies to refugees in this way.
But there are still pragmatic options that we can utilize.
In April last year, I went to Jordan with my colleague, development economist Paul Collier, and we reflected on an idea we had there with the international community and the government, an idea to create jobs for Syrians while supporting Jordan's national development strategy.
It is the idea of an economic zone where we could potentially integrate the employment of refugees as well as the employment of the natives of the host country.
Fifteen minutes from the Zaatari camp, which hosts 83,000 refugees, is the King Hussein Bin Talal Development Zone.
The government spent over 100 million dollars to connect it to the electrical grid and the road network, but two things were missing: access to labor and foreign investments.
so that refugees can work there instead of being stuck in camps, support their families, and develop skills through vocational training before returning to Syria.
We recognized that Jordan would benefit from this, as its development strategy requires making the leap from a middle-income country to an industrialized nation.
Refugees would benefit from this, but it would also contribute to the reconstruction of Syria after the war, recognizing that we must nurture the refugees as they are the best resource for rebuilding Syria.
We published this idea in Foreign Affairs.
King Abdullah has taken up the idea.
This was announced at the London Conference on Syria, and a trial will begin during the summer.
The third idea I want to present to you is the notion of preference between states and refugees leading to positive outcomes, as you can see in this selfie featuring Angela Merkel and a Syrian refugee.
We rarely ask refugees what they want, where they want to go, but we can do so, and it will be better for everyone.
The economist Alvin Roth developed the idea of market matching, where the preference order of the parties determines their potential match.
My colleagues Will Jones and Alex Teytelboym have explored ways to apply this idea to refugees, asking refugees to rank destinations while also allowing states to rank the types of refugees desired based on skills or languages, and then matching them accordingly.
Of course, quotas should be established regarding diversity and vulnerability, but this is a way to increase the chances of matching.
The idea of matching is successfully used, for example, to allocate students at universities, match kidney donors with patients, and the algorithm exists on dating sites.
Why not apply this to give refugees a choice?
This could also be used at the national level, where one of the biggest challenges is to persuade local communities to accept refugees.
Currently, in my country, for example, we often send engineers to rural areas and farmers to the city, which makes no sense.
Market matching allows for the alignment of these preferences and listens to the needs and demands of the host population and the refugees.
The fourth idea I want to discuss is the principle of humanitarian visas.
The tragedies and upheavals observed in Europe could have been avoided.
They stem from a fundamental contradiction in European asylum policy: in order to apply for asylum in Europe, you must arrive spontaneously by embarking on a dangerous journey that I have already mentioned.
But why are these journeys necessary in the age of low-cost airlines and modern consular means?
These journeys are not necessary and, last year, they led to the deaths of more than 3,000 people at the borders of Europe and on European territory.
If refugees had the right to travel directly and apply for asylum in Europe, we could avoid this. And we can do this through humanitarian visas that allow people to obtain a visa from an embassy or consulate of a neighboring country and then pay for their ferry or flight to Europe.
